  • Felon Possess Firearm, a class G felony, Wisconsin Statutes 941.29(2)(a).

Count 2:  COURT ORDERS defendant to serve a term in the Wisconsin State Prison system - TOTAL LENGTH OF SENTENCE - 60 months with 186 days credit; INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT - 30 months; EXTENDED SUPERVISION - 30 months - concurrent with Count 1; pay mandatory costs, assessments and surcharges by the end of the sentence or a civil judgment is to be entered against the defendant and subject to other collection.

Count 3:  COURT ORDERS defendant to serve a term in the Wisconsin State Prison system - TOTAL LENGTH OF SENTENCE - 60 months with 186 days credit; INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT - 30 months; EXTENDED SUPERVISION - 30 months - concurrent with Count 1; pay mandatory costs, assessments and surcharges by the end of the sentence or a civil judgment is to be entered against the defendant and subject to other collection.

Court finds defendant is not eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program or the Substance Abuse Program.CONDITIONS OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION:  1) no violations of criminal law rising to the level of probable cause; 2) pay any monetary amounts ordered but not paid while in the institution; 3) AODA, programs or treatment as recommended; 4) do not use or possess illegally controlled substances; 5) random screening. 

COURT ORDERS:
- DOC to collect monetary sums/amounts at the rate of 25% of prison funds;
- defendant to provide a biological specimen for DNA analysis.

Appeal rights given.  Written Explanation of Determinate Sentence, Notice of Right to Seek Postconviction Relief, Pretrial Incarceration Credit and Ineligible Voting Notice and Acknowledgment received and filed.  Copies given to the defendant.

Sentencing proceeds.   Statements by counsel.  

COURT ADVISES the defendant he cannot possess firearms or body armor, he must provide a DNA sample, if this conviction is reversed, set aside or vacated you may qualify to have the DNA sample data expunged if you meet conditions under the statute and cannot vote until his civil rights are restored.
